{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505238"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2423"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2423"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.6,0.23,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2423"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1882"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of cramping left-sided abdominal pain. The pain starts in his flank and radiates down into his scrotum. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft to palpation with left renal angle tenderness. Urinalysis shows haemoglobin +++. Intramuscular diclofenac provides partial pain relief. A computed tomography scan reveals a 6mm stone at the lower end of the left ureter with mild left hydronephrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the strongest indication for urgent surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abnormal vital signs","Impaired renal function","Intractable pain despite analgesia","Renal angle tenderness","Urinalysis showing haematuria"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of renal colic. While several factors may influence the decision for surgical intervention, some indications are more urgent than others. \u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired renal function\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the strongest indications for urgent intervention as it suggests significant obstruction that could lead to permanent kidney damage if not addressed promptly. Even a short period of complete obstruction can cause irreversible nephron loss, and prolonged obstruction may result in permanent loss of kidney function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal vital signs\u003C/strong\u003E alone, such as mild tachycardia, are not necessarily an indication for urgent intervention unless accompanied by fever suggesting urosepsis. Tachycardia is often due to pain and anxiety in renal colic. However, if fever develops (\u003E38\u00b0C), this suggests infection above the obstruction (obstructive pyelonephritis) which is a surgical emergency requiring immediate decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntractable pain despite analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E is a relative indication for intervention, but not as urgent as impaired renal function or signs of infection. Most patients achieve adequate pain control with appropriate analgesia including non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and opioids. Pain that is truly refractory to maximal medical therapy may warrant earlier intervention, but this is not an emergency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal angle tenderness\u003C/strong\u003E is a typical finding in renal colic and alone does not indicate the need for urgent intervention. It is present in most cases of renal colic due to inflammation and distension of the renal capsule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinalysis showing haematuria\u003C/strong\u003E is an expected finding in renal colic and does not indicate the need for intervention. Microscopic or macroscopic haematuria is present in up to 85% of cases of renal colic due to mucosal irritation from the stone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of ureteric stones depends on several factors including stone size, location, and presence of complications. Stones less than 5mm generally pass spontaneously with conservative management. Stones 5-10mm have a variable chance of spontaneous passage, while stones larger than 10mm almost always require intervention. The options for stone removal include extracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy (ESWL), ureteroscopy with laser lithotripsy, or in some cases, percutaneous nephrolithotomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Impaired renal function in a patient with a ureteric stone is an absolute indication for urgent surgical intervention.","Stones \u003E7mm are unlikely to pass spontaneously and may require intervention.","Fever suggesting urosepsis is another absolute indication for urgent intervention in renal colic.","Most ureteric stones \u003C5mm will pass spontaneously with conservative management."],"references":["Sewell J, Katz DJ, Shoshany O, Love C. Urolithiasis \u2013 Ten things every general practitioner should know. Australian Family Physician. 2017; 46:9 (648-652).","Zumstein V, Beschert P, Abt D, Schmid HP, Panne CM, Putora PM. Surgical management of urolithiasis \u2013 a systematic analysis of available guidelines. BMC Urol. 2018; 18 (25)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2423"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18360"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18360"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eb2644a-55bc-43b5-9ce3-e8cff307c286.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eb2644a-55bc-43b5-9ce3-e8cff307c286.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":332}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T12:08:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T12:10:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2423"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud8